metadata.name: Reading a book #473
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: AutomatonII #11
metadata.description: Automaton I and Automaton II began life as the sleeve artwork for a concept LP about automata - self propelling machines, puppets and models that were once the heralds of a bright, technological future. Referencing retro-futurism, VHS idents and 70s pulp sci-fi covers, these generative pieces evoke mysterious, immersive spaces, using simple geometry and a random walking algorithm.

metadata.name: chorégraphie #303
metadata.description:
… divided in two,
like the parent in sound and motion.
yet not exactly the same, I get …


chorégraphie explores the algorithmic characteristics of recursion in audiovisual form.

The algorithm performs a recursive split. At each split stage, space is divided into four different sized quadrants. Each split stage will eventually spawn an oscillator or a synthesizer representing the current properties of recursion in sound. The process is recursively repeated until a maximum recursion depth is reached or an early return condition is met.
Additionally, an initial motion funnction is randomly selected and propageted through the recursion, so that each recursive split stage with move depending on it’s split properties in combination with time.

Click into the piece to start the audio. Each piece can be seeded with a new initial configuration by pressing the ‘s’ key.

© 2022 — Guido Schmidt

Created with:
p5, tone, @thi.ng/color, random

metadata.name: Abstract Attractorism #226
metadata.description:
Painted strange attractors in charcoal, acrylic, and colored pencils.

The piece has several phases: background, charcoal sketch, painting, finishing, and then starting over building up layers.

For each seed, the first painting is consistent for all platforms. Paintings after that may slightly vary between browsers. 

Press 'p' to pause and 's' to take a screenshot at any time. The image size is 1400x1082 which is the aspect ratio of a standard printer paper.

Features
- 200 possible palettes
- 3 possible color distribution methods
- 50% colored pencil border on completion
- Distribution of brush qualities and color variance from the palette colors

20% chance of rare
- More variation in the attractor functions for more unique results
- Small brush strokes with a longer paint time

10% chance of super rare
- Everything from rare
- Guaranteed large color blocks instead of smaller chaotic random color distribution
- Tape border when it's finished

metadata.name: Bound #291
metadata.description:
Knots bind and hold, mark time, and unite. But the power of a well-tied knot isn't only to fasten – it also symbolizes how tightly one holds their pledges. Whether a commitment to a partner, community, or oneself – the longevity of a deeply held bond is often marked with a symbol of passing time, like knots tied in a rope.

Let these ropes remind us of the binds we hold – new ones, lengthy ones, unbreakable ones, and even those we’ve had to untie. In plain view, these knots invite us to contemplate what our bonds mean to us, and to see them anew.
